y modern drama. Key FeaturesProvides the first account of the place of judgment in Shakespearean dramaOffers a fresh perspective on the imaginative relationship between law, religion, and aesthetics in Shakespeare’s playsModels new ways of putting the plays’ historical and philosophical contexts into conversation  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aJudgment in literature. 0aLaw in literature. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLAW / Jurisprudence.2bisacsh1 aAttié, Katherine B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBudick, Sanford, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurran, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJordan, Constance, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParker, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSale, Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSoni, Vivasvan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrain, Virginia Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrier, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYachnin, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311078044440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147441316940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474413169423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474413169/original  a978-3-11-078044-4  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  